Coastal, KPJ, Mulpha, Shangri-La, Time: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   B a r r y   P o r t e r   a n d   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-05-23T00:15:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-23/coastal-kpj-mulpha-shangri-la-time-malaysia-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise. The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index fell 0.2
percent to 1,541.03 on May 20.  Coastal Contracts Bhd. (COCO)  : The shipbuilder mutually
agreed to end an agreement with Ramunia Holdings Bhd. (RH MK) to
jointly bid for projects in the oil and gas industry, according
to an exchange filing. Coastal Contracts lost 1.7 percent to
3.58 ringgit. Ramunia slid 0.9 percent to 52.5 sen.  KPJ Healthcare Bhd. (KPJ)  : The health-care group’s
first-quarter net income rose 1 percent from a year earlier to
27.5 million ringgit ($9.1 million), according to a company
statement. The stock dropped 1.2 percent to 4.16 ringgit.  Mulpha International Bhd. (MIT)  : The property
developer’s first-quarter net income more than tripled from a
year earlier to 178.7 million ringgit, the company said in a
statement. Mulpha advanced 1 percent to 51 sen.  Malaysia Smelting Corp. (SMELT MK): The world’s third-
biggest tin producer signed a confidentiality agreement with the
Democratic Republic of Congo to develop mineral concessions in
the war-torn east, Congo’s mines minister said. The company will
take over mineral concessions in Maniema, North Kivu and South
Kivu provinces from the government-owned miner Sakima, Mines
Minister  Martin Kabwelulu  said on May 21. The stock was
unchanged at 4.87 ringgit.  Petrol One Resources Bhd. (PORB MK): The oil and gas
services provider proposed to raise as much as 62.7 million
ringgit from a rights offer and share placement to help fund
expansion and repay bank borrowings, according to a company
statement. The stock retreated 0.6 percent to 1.60 ringgit.       Shangri-La Hotels Malaysia Bhd. (SHMB MK): The hotel
operator’s first-quarter net income rose 24 percent from a year
earlier to 20.6 million ringgit, according to an exchange
filing. The stock fell 0.4 percent to 2.65 ringgit.        Time Engineering Bhd. (TIM)  : The telecommunications
services provider had a net loss of 2.93 million ringgit in the
first quarter, compared with a profit of 871,000 ringgit a year
earlier, as sales dropped, it said in a stock exchange filing
said. Time was unchanged at 49 sen.  To contact the reporters on this story:
